# Phase 212.M-F.8 — PX4 SITL board overlay for nano-ros component modules.
#
# `nros codegen-system --ahead-of-vendor --target px4` emits one
# `nros_<name>/` module dir per component under `$PX4_AUTOPILOT_DIR/src/modules/`.
# PX4's own SITL build (`make px4_sitl_default`) doesn't pick those up
# unless the per-module Kconfig switch is flipped ON in a `.px4board`
# fragment under `boards/px4/sitl/`.
#
# This file is a **template** — it's not consumed by PX4 directly. The
# operator copies the rendered output of `render-overlay.sh` into the
# PX4 tree (typically `boards/px4/sitl/default.px4board`, or a sibling
# `nros.px4board` board variant).
#
# Lines below are KConfig-style assignments. The exact module switch
# name comes from each per-component Kconfig the codegen emits:
#
#     menuconfig MODULES_NROS_<UPPER>
#
# (see `integrations/px4/module-template/component-skeleton/Kconfig`
#  for the template the codegen renders against). To enable a module,
# add a matching `CONFIG_MODULES_NROS_<UPPER>=y` line below.
#
# The placeholder gets expanded by `render-overlay.sh`, which walks
# `$PX4_AUTOPILOT_DIR/src/modules/nros_*/` and emits one
# `CONFIG_MODULES_NROS_<UPPER>=y` line per emitted module dir. The
# operator then concatenates the rendered fragment onto the SITL
# `.px4board` of their choice (PX4 reads `.px4board` files as a single
# Kconfig defconfig — concatenation is the supported merge mechanism).

# === BEGIN nano-ros component modules ===
@NROS_MODULES_ENABLE@
# === END nano-ros component modules ===
